4. JS Search:

- String Search Methods:
    String indexOf()
    String lastIndexOf()
    String search()
    String match()
    String matchAll()
    String includes()
    String startsWith()
    String endsWith()


1) String indexOf():
    - The indexOf() method returns the index (position) of the first occurrence of a string in a string,
        or it returns -1 if the string is not found:
    - It searches from left to right.

        eg:
            let text = "Please locate where 'locate' occurs!";
            let index = text.indexOf("locate"); // 7

    - âš ï¸ JavaScript counts positions from zero.


2) String lastIndexOf():
    - The lastIndexOf() method returns the index of the last occurrence of a specified text in a string:
    - It searches from right to left(backward)
        eg:
            let text = "Please locate where 'locate' occurs!";
            let index = text.lastIndexOf("locate"); // 21
    
    - âš ï¸ Both indexOf(), and lastIndexOf() return -1 if the text is not found:
    - Both methods accept a second parameter as the starting position for the search:

            let text = "Please locate where 'locate' occurs!";
            let index = text.indexOf("locate", 15); // 21

            let text = "Please locate where 'locate' occurs!";
            text.lastIndexOf("locate", 15); // 7


3) String search():
    - The search() method searches a string for a string (or a regular expression) and returns the position
        of the match:
        eg:
            let text = "Please locate where 'locate' occurs!";
            text.search("locate");  // 7

            or

            let text = "Please locate where 'locate' occurs!";
            text.search(/locate/);  // 7

ðŸ’¡Although the indexOf() and search() looks similar, they are not.
    ðŸ‘‰ The search() method cannot take a second start position argument.
    ðŸ‘‰ The indexOf() method cannot take powerful search values (regular expressions).


4) String match():
    - The match() method returns an array containing the results of matching a string against a string
        (or a regular expression).
        eg: 
            let text = "The rain in SPAIN stays mainly in the plain";
            text.match("ain");  // 1 ain

            or

            let text = "The rain in SPAIN stays mainly in the plain";
            text.match(/ain/);  // 1 ain
    
    - Perform a global search for "ain":

            let text = "The rain in SPAIN stays mainly in the plain";
            text.match(/ain/g); // 3 ain,ain,ain
    
    - Perform a global, case-insensitive search for "ain":

            let text = "The rain in SPAIN stays mainly in the plain";
            text.match(/ain/gi);    // 4 ain,AIN,ain,ain
    
    - If a regular expression does not include the g modifier (global search), match() will return only
        the first match in the string.


5) String matchAll(): is an ES2020 feature.
    - The matchAll() method returns an iterator containing the results of matching a string against a
        string (or a regular expression).

            let text = "I love cats. Cats are very easy to love. Cats are very popular."
            const iterator = text.matchAll("Cats"); // Cats,Cats

    - If the parameter is a regular expression, the global flag (g) must be set, otherwise a TypeError
        is thrown.

            let text = "I love cats. Cats are very easy to love. Cats are very popular."
            const iterator = text.matchAll(/Cats/g); // Cats,Cats
    
    - If you want to search case insensitive, the insensitive flag (i) must be set:

            const iterator = text.matchAll(/Cats/gi);


6) String includes(): is an ES6 feature.
    - The includes() method returns true if a string contains a specified value. Otherwise it returns false.

            let text = "Hello world, welcome to the universe.";
            text.includes("world"); // true
        
        -> Check if a string includes "world". Start at position 12:

            let text = "Hello world, welcome to the universe.";
            text.includes("world", 12); // false
    
    - includes() is case sensitive.


7) String startsWith(): is an ES6 feature.
    - The startsWith() method returns true if a string begins with a specified value. Otherwise it returns
        false:

            let text = "Hello world, welcome to the universe.";
            text.startsWith("Hello");   // true

            let text = "Hello world, welcome to the universe.";
            text.startsWith("world")    // false
        
        -> A start position for the search can be specified:

            let text = "Hello world, welcome to the universe.";
            text.startsWith("world", 5) // false

            let text = "Hello world, welcome to the universe.";
            text.startsWith("world", 6)
    
    - startsWith() is case sensitive.


8) String endsWith(): is an ES6 feature.
    - The endsWith() method returns true if a string ends with a specified value. Otherwise it returns false:

            let text = "John Doe";
            text.endsWith("oe");   // true
        
        -> Check if the 11 first characters of a string ends with "world":

            let text = "Hello world, welcome to the universe.";
            text.endsWith("world", 11); // true
    
    - endsWith() is case sensitive.